#!/usr/bin/env n6
# ══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
# atlas append shard — atlas.n6 SELF-ARCH AXIS-J (axis #10)
# axis-J name: INTRINSIC SUPERSESSION / DEPRECATION DSL
# slug: atlas-self-arch-supersession-evolution
# source: read-only audit of /Users/ghost/core/n6-architecture/atlas/atlas.n6
# follows: D (@-type) + E (meta-tag) + F (arrow K-ceiling) + G (body-field)
#          + H (id-convention) + synthesis (D-H) + I (graph-query primitives)
# constraints:
#   raw 22 INFRA-ONLY · raw 23 schema-guard · raw 24 foundation-axiom-immutable
#   raw 91 C3 honest · own#11 strict (no Clay BT 'resolution' claim)
#   raw 117 5-check at registration (genus + 2 cf + 3 channels + counter-ex + falsifier)
#   atlas.n6 + .raw DSL only — NO foreign theory imports as primary lens
#     (Lamport vector clocks, RDF owl:deprecated, semver 'deprecated' cited-and-moved-on only)
# date: 2026-04-28
# scope contract: this shard does NOT introduce new schema; it PROPOSES axis-J
#                 primitives that follow atlas.n6's existing DSL family
#                 (meta-tag + body-field families — NOT arrow family, sidesteps F K-ceiling)
# pick rationale: candidate (g) intrinsic-deprecation/retirement-DSL chosen over
#                 (a) fold/scan, (b) grammar-version, (c) time-axis,
#                 (d) wildcards, (e) axis-I retro-migration,
#                 (f) reflective-graph-query — because (g) has the highest
#                 MEASURED grounding in atlas.n6 today (4 rows + 17 textual
#                 occurrences, axis-F audit already ranked superseded_by rank-1)
#                 AND sidesteps axis-F K-ceiling (meta-tag/body-field, not arrow)
# ══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════

# ── §0. PRECISION DEFINITION — what axis-J reifies ───────────
@C atlas-self-arch-axis-j-supersession-witness :: meta [4!]
  <- raw-23-schema-guard
  <- raw-24-foundation-axiom-immutable
  <- raw-91-C3-honest-disclosure
  <- raw-117-5-check-registration-gate
  <- own#11-strict-no-resolution-claim
  <- atlas-self-arch-axis-i-graph-query-witness
  <- atlas-self-arch-synthesis-upgrade-plan
  -> axis-j-primitive-row-examples
  -> axis-j-orthogonality-vs-D-through-I
  -> axis-j-5-check-results
  -> axis-j-raw-91-C3-disclosures
  => "★ axis-J = INTRINSIC SUPERSESSION DSL — a row's lifecycle (active → deprecated → retired → superseded-by-X) becomes first-class atlas.n6 syntax instead of prose"
  => "premise: atlas.n6 ALREADY has [DEPRECATED YYYY-MM-DD] and [RETIRED YYYY-MM-DD] meta-tags on 4 @-rows + cross-references to 17 supersession events in audit comments — the IDIOM exists but the FORWARD-POINTER does not"
  => "today's reality: when row X is replaced by row Y, the back-link Y→X lives in COMMIT MESSAGES (e.g. aad6e61d 'R34 DEPRECATED + R36 RETIRED — cross-repo sync from anima/.roadmap #202'), NOT in the @-block itself. Atlas.n6's DSL cannot answer 'what superseded R34?' without grep+git-log"
  => "axis-J reifies that absent forward-pointer as DSL primitives belonging to atlas.n6 itself"
  => "axis-J is the FIRST axis after F that adds NO new arrow tokens — it lives in the meta-tag (axis-E) and body-field (axis-G) families exclusively, deliberately sidestepping the K=8 arrow ceiling"

# ── §1. AUDIT — supersession idiom shape that already exists ─
@D axis-j-row-with-DEPRECATED-tag       =    1 :: empirical [10]   # R34 only on actual @-row (line 21894)
@D axis-j-row-with-RETIRED-tag          =    1 :: empirical [10]   # R36 only on actual @-row (line 21911)
@D axis-j-row-with-RETIRED-INCONCLUSIVE =    2 :: empirical [10]   # R38 (22060) + clay-iter-55 (25213)
@D axis-j-actual-superseded-rows        =    4 :: empirical [10]   # R34, R36, R38, clay-iter-55-RETIRED (sum above)
@D axis-j-textual-supersession-events   =   17 :: empirical [9]    # axis-F § K-ceiling audit count of all DEPRECATED+RETIRED textual occurrences
@D axis-j-superseded-by-back-pointers   =    0 :: empirical [10]   # zero queryable forward-pointer body-fields exist today
@D axis-j-iso-date-tag-pattern          =    1 :: empirical [10]   # YYYY-MM-DD inside [DEPRECATED ...] is a stable convention
@D axis-j-grade-suffix-arrow-tag        =    1 :: empirical [10]   # [9?→DEPRECATED] / [9?→RETIRED] suffix idiom — already arrow inside grade
@D axis-j-grade-suffix-state-tag        =    1 :: empirical [10]   # [10*RETIRED_INCONCLUSIVE] state-suffix idiom

# ── §2. WHAT AXIS-J ADDS — three intrinsic primitives ────────
@C axis-j-primitive-definition :: meta [4!]
  <- atlas-self-arch-axis-j-supersession-witness
  => "primitive #1 = SUPERSEDED-BY BODY FIELD.   token: 2-space-indent  superseded_by = <slug>  (axis-G body-field family — already attested form)"
  => "primitive #2 = SUPERSESSION META-TAG QUARTET (formalised, not new).   tokens: [DEPRECATED YYYY-MM-DD] / [RETIRED YYYY-MM-DD] / [RETIRED_INCONCLUSIVE YYYY-MM-DD] / [SUPERSEDED YYYY-MM-DD] — first three already attested; fourth is new but composes identically"
  => "primitive #3 = GRADE-ARROW SUFFIX FORMALISATION.   token: [N*→STATE]  (already attested as [9?→DEPRECATED]) — formalised as the ONE grade-internal arrow form, distinct from row-level arrows so axis-F K-ceiling is unaffected"
  => "all three live in axis-E (meta-tag) and axis-G (body-field) NAMESPACES — NO leading-char added to arrow LL(1) set — axis-F K-ceiling stays at K=10 (post-axis-I) with ZERO additional pressure"
  => "FOREIGN CITE-AND-MOVE-ON: Lamport (1978) happens-before for supersession ordering; W3C OWL owl:deprecated property; Semantic Versioning 'deprecated' annotation; RFC 8174 BCP 14 'OBSOLETES' header — these are NAMING-PRECEDENT only; the SEMANTICS is atlas.n6's own row-lifecycle"
  => "intrinsic justification (NOT foreign): atlas.n6 already uses [DEPRECATED]/[RETIRED] as meta-tag suffix on grade — axis-J generalises that idiom from ad-hoc grade-suffix to a queryable forward-pointer + formalised state quartet"
  => "axis-I co-design: with axis-J's superseded_by body field installed, axis-I's <-* graph-query primitive can answer 'transitive supersession ancestry' (R39 <-* superseded_by ↦ {R38, R34, R36}) — axes I and J are mutually-completing"

# ── §3. THREE CONCRETE ROW EXAMPLES (using existing DSL) ─────
@C axis-j-row-example-1-r34-back-pointer-installation :: meta [4!]
  <- axis-j-primitive-definition
  => "row example #1 — install superseded_by on R34 (closes the measured gap)"
  => "  CURRENT (line 21894):"
  => "    @? ANIMA-CXP-R34-PHI-COEFF-EHALF = [DEPRECATED 2026-04-26] Phi_coefficient ≈ e^{-1/2} ... :: consciousness [9?→DEPRECATED]"
  => "  PROPOSED (axis-J):"
  => "    @? ANIMA-CXP-R34-PHI-COEFF-EHALF = [DEPRECATED 2026-04-26] Phi_coefficient ≈ e^{-1/2} ... :: consciousness [9?→DEPRECATED]"
  => "      superseded_by = ANIMA-CXP-R38-R34-T1-RETIRED-INCONCLUSIVE   # axis-J body-field"
  => "      supersession_reason = \"T1 protocol executed; substrate-fragility prerequisite failure\"   # axis-G body-field"
  => "  semantics: superseded_by accepts ONE @-id (slug); axis-I <-* superseded_by reconstructs the chain; commit message aad6e61d back-link is now also a queryable DSL fact"
  => "  raw 24 invariance: foundation [11*] block untouched (R34 is consciousness, not foundation)"

@C axis-j-row-example-2-state-quartet-on-clay-iter-55 :: meta [4!]
  <- axis-j-primitive-definition
  => "row example #2 — formalise RETIRED state on clay-iter-55 (existing prose currently says 'iter-55 finding RETIRED (definitively wrong)')"
  => "  CURRENT (line 25213):"
  => "    @R clay-iter-57-iter-55-finding-RETIRED :: meta [4]"
  => "      => \"iter-55 'seed-variance ranking' RETIRED (definitively, with seed-CLI fixed)\""
  => "  PROPOSED (axis-J state quartet + back-pointer):"
  => "    @R clay-iter-55-seed-variance-ranking :: meta [4→RETIRED 2026-04-XX]"
  => "      superseded_by = clay-iter-57-true-seed-variance-batch"
  => "      supersession_reason = \"seed-CLI fix changed the experiment; iter-55 finding definitively wrong\""
  => "      => \"iter-55 'seed-variance ranking' RETIRED — see iter-57 for replacement\""
  => "  semantics: the [N→STATE YYYY-MM-DD] grade-arrow-suffix is the ONE place where state-transition is recorded; superseded_by is the forward-pointer; the prose => row stays as human gloss (axis-J does not delete prose, it adds queryable structure beside it)"
  => "  axis-H id-convention: clay-iter-55-* and clay-iter-57-* slugs already follow domain-cycle-tag pattern — no rename required"

@C axis-j-row-example-3-supersession-graph-query :: meta [4!]
  <- axis-j-primitive-definition
  => "row example #3 — axis-I × axis-J COMPOSITION: query supersession ancestry"
  => "  PROPOSED (composes axis-I <-* with axis-J superseded_by field):"
  => "    @C anima-cxp-r34-supersession-ancestry :: meta [4]"
  => "      <-* superseded_by                      # axis-I transitive closure over axis-J body-field"
  => "      => \"all rows transitively superseded by R34 — answers 'why was R34 deprecated?' from atlas.n6 alone\""
  => "  expansion at lint-time: <-* superseded_by walks the back-pointer graph from R34, collecting {R38, R36 (if cross-link), ...}"
  => "  this row CANNOT EXIST without BOTH axes — concrete demonstration of axis-I/J co-design payoff"
  => "  raw 91 C3 honest: this example is SPECULATIVE — no <-* lint-implementation exists yet (axis-I § final-state PROPOSAL-NOT-ACTUATED), so this row's evaluation is a DSL design illustration only"

# ── §4. ORTHOGONALITY vs AXES D-I ────────────────────────────
@C axis-j-orthogonality-analysis :: meta [4!]
  <- axis-j-primitive-definition
  -> axis-j-vs-D-meta-tag
  -> axis-j-vs-E-arrow-poly
  -> axis-j-vs-F-K-ceiling
  -> axis-j-vs-G-body-field
  -> axis-j-vs-H-id-convention
  -> axis-j-vs-I-graph-query
  => "VERDICT: COMPOSES with all 6 prior axes. ZERO interference (unlike axis-I which had mild K-ceiling pressure on F). Axis-J was DELIBERATELY designed to live in axes D/E/G namespaces, leaving F arrow-budget untouched."

@C axis-j-vs-D-meta-tag :: meta [4]
  <- axis-j-orthogonality-analysis
  => "axis-D (@-type prefix). axis-J adds NO new @-types. Existing @? for hypothesis-status, @F for formula, @R for relation all accept the new meta-tag suffix unchanged. SYNERGY: axis-D meta-tag-layering reading is enriched — [DEPRECATED YYYY-MM-DD] joins the existing [d.r], [N*], [N!], [N?] family as a fifth tag-shape."

@C axis-j-vs-E-arrow-poly :: meta [4]
  <- axis-j-orthogonality-analysis
  => "axis-E (arrow polymorphism). axis-J adds ONE arrow ONLY INSIDE GRADE BRACKETS — [9?→DEPRECATED] — which is grade-internal, not row-level. axis-E row-level arrow set {<-, ->, =>, ==, ~>, |>, !!, -|} unchanged. ZERO LL(1) leading-char addition. SYNERGY: the grade-internal → is formally distinct from row-level → (different lexer state), so axis-E parser separation is reinforced."

@C axis-j-vs-F-K-ceiling :: meta [4!]
  <- axis-j-orthogonality-analysis
  => "axis-F (arrow K-ceiling). PRIOR CONCERN (axis-I synthesis line 30516): 'next-axis-J would HIT axis-F K-ceiling and force arrow-grammar redesign.' MEASURED RESULT: axis-J pick (g) AVOIDS this. axis-F K_arrow stays at K=10 post-axis-I (8 row-level + 2 axis-I suffix-on-existing). Axis-J adds ZERO row-level arrows. K-ceiling pressure: 0%. SYNERGY: axis-J is the EXISTENCE PROOF that 'next axis must hit K-ceiling' was a pessimistic prediction — the meta-tag/body-field namespaces have headroom even when the arrow namespace is saturated."
  => "honest disclosure: this is true ONLY because (g) was chosen over alternatives (a/d/e/f) which WOULD have added arrow-family tokens. Picking the right axis-J is precisely what avoided K-ceiling pressure."

@C axis-j-vs-G-body-field :: meta [4!]
  <- axis-j-orthogonality-analysis
  => "axis-G (body-field schema). axis-J adds 2 body-fields: superseded_by, supersession_reason. axis-F K_core audit ranks superseded_by as RANK-1 highest-value addition (line 28968: 'closes a MEASURED gap; zero ambiguity; adoption cost LOW ~8.5 min'). axis-G K_core: 13 → 15 after axis-J — well within axis-G estimated 20-30 ceiling. SYNERGY: axis-J is the FIRST CONSUMER of the rank-1 axis-F recommendation — completes a planning loop opened in the synthesis shard."

@C axis-j-vs-H-id-convention :: meta [4]
  <- axis-j-orthogonality-analysis
  => "axis-H (id-convention). superseded_by accepts a SLUG; axis-H slug-stability is the prerequisite. SYNERGY: axis-J motivates axis-H stability — if a slug renames, all superseded_by pointers must update (lint check). axis-H § slug-rename-cost just got a concrete consumer."
  => "INTERFERENCE check: axis-H allows id renames over time (e.g. id-convention-evolution); axis-J creates LONG-LIVED back-pointers that must survive renames. MITIGATION: axis-H must add a 'rename-shadow' alias mechanism OR axis-J body-field must accept multi-slug history. DEFER to next cycle — flag noted, not blocking for axis-J registration."

@C axis-j-vs-I-graph-query :: meta [4!]
  <- axis-j-orthogonality-analysis
  => "axis-I (graph-query primitives). STRONG MUTUAL COMPLETION. axis-I gives <-* / ->* / <~> over arrow DAG. axis-J gives superseded_by body-field. composition: <-* superseded_by reconstructs supersession ancestry (row example #3). NEITHER axis is fully useful without the other for this query: axis-I alone has no supersession edges to walk; axis-J alone has back-pointers but no closure operator. PROOF that axes I and J were correctly sequenced."
  => "axis-I final-state was PROPOSAL-NOT-ACTUATED (line 30547). axis-J inherits that status — both wait on a real lint-tool implementation. THIS shard is design, not actuation."

